{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"220688de-a4be-49db-8b72-f9c5af2b4ab9","content":"There's no project at that path yet. Here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a global/local dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users invoke (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer` then run `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — required for stdio-based MCP servers.\n\n### Publishing steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — no `.nuspec` file required. The `PackAsTool` property handles the rest.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"545165da-222a-4410-827c-0195d1ba4cc5","outputTokens":512,"requestId":"7006:2D337E:137C14C:16B9F0C:69EC124C"},"id":"53dfbe69-3766-4371-9ed4-c1b36791170c","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:01:09.819Z","parentId":"c98472c8-a95c-4d7c-8b55-53e9afc30942"}
